@jerryshao I'm sorry for delay with response.

> When user runs Spark on k8s, user could configure the different properties to let Spark to honor. 

Do you know if we can do the same with k8s/docker and Livy now? Probably, I was not aware about that, It would be great if we can.

> I'm wondering why do have to use env variables for docker image?

@RyanSkraba perfectly explained above our use case, different ways how we could go and, actually, it was simplest and only possible solution for that moment but probably we missed something.  

What are the disadvantages and obstacles of proposed solution with env variables, that prevents this PR to be merged, from your point of you?

@jerryshao thanks for you review.

The main reason for copying the classes from Hive are:

 1. We need to override private methods, so either we do it using reflection and kind of rewriting some methods using reflection or copying the Hive code and doing some very small changes about visibility and very small changes in order to make the code easier to extend (this is the least important reason);
 2. Avoid metastore access from the server, which is otherwise intrinsic in Hive codebase;
 3. This needs further investigation, but the UGI management which is performed automatically by Hive may need to be removed/adjusted in order not to interfere with the one performed by Livy.

I think that the 1 issue can be easily addressed by cooperating with the Hive community, but the other 2 points may be more critical to address. I'd consider the current situation as a workaround which will be replaced by using only Hive's artifacts once we can  solve the 3 points above with the help of the Hive community.
